<Document>
<name>Stuart Highway — Alice Springs to Port Augusta</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Stuart Highway — Alice Springs to Port Augusta</h2><p><i>Northern Territory / South Australia · Stuart Highway, Alice Springs to Port Augusta</i></p><p><b>1,225 km through the empty centre — the modern path of John McDouall Stuart's 1862 south-to-north crossing.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>1146 km (712 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (summer is dangerously hot)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Road trains 50 m long, kangaroos at dawn/dusk, fuel stops 200+ km apart, extreme heat in summer, distance-induced micro-sleeps</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>1151</td></tr></table><hr><p>John McDouall Stuart led the first European crossing of Australia from south to north in 1862, from Adelaide to the Top End — and lost his sight by the end of it. The Overland Telegraph followed his route in 1872, the railway followed it in stages over the next century, and the modern Stuart Highway, fully sealed only in 1987, traces the same line. From Alice Springs the road climbs the slow rise of the central plateau, drops into opal country at Coober Pedy (where summer heat drives most residents to live underground), then crosses the empty plain to Port Augusta on Spencer Gulf. The horizon-to-horizon emptiness is the point. Carry water. Refuel at every roadhouse.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Erldunda</b> — Junction with the Lasseter Highway to Uluru. Roadhouse with an emu farm — the cassowary's slightly less impressive desert cousin. Last reasonable supplies before Coober Pedy.</li><li><b>Coober Pedy</b> — Opal-mining town producing ~70% of the world's opal. Summer surface temperatures pass 45 °C; most homes, shops, churches, and hotels are underground in disused mine workings. Tour a 'dugout' home.</li><li><b>Glendambo</b> — Population sign reads 'Sheep 22,500 / Flies 2,000,000 / People 30.' Roadhouse with caravan park; nothing else. Long, flat, treeless plain begins to lift toward the Flinders Ranges.</li><li><b>Woomera (turnoff)</b> — Cold War rocket-test range — UK and Australian missile testing site from 1947. Open-air museum of decommissioned missiles and aircraft (free). Active range still — observe the warning signs.</li><li><b>Port Augusta</b> — Where the desert meets Spencer Gulf. The Australian Arid Lands Botanic Garden on the northern outskirts is the best collection of central-Australian flora anywhere. Flinders Ranges visible to the east.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
